  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "How do I send 16-bit data to Arduino using Simulink?",
  "response": "To send 16-bit data to an Arduino using Simulink, you can use the Simulink Support Package for Arduino. This package provides blocks that allow you to interface with Arduino hardware directly from Simulink. Here\u2019s a step-by-step guide:\n\n### Step 1: Install the Simulink Support Package for Arduino\n1. Open MATLAB.\n2. In the MATLAB Command Window, type `supportPackageInstaller` and press Enter.\n3. In the Support Package Installer, select \"Simulink Support Package for Arduino\" and follow the instructions to install it.\n\n### Step 2: Create a Simulink Model\n1. Open Simulink by typing `simulink` in the MATLAB Command Window and press Enter.\n2. Create a new Simulink model.\n\n### Step 3: Add Blocks to the Model\n1. **Constant Block**: \n   - Add a `Constant` block from the Simulink Library Browser (`Simulink > Sources`).\n   - Set the constant value to the 16-bit data you want to send. You can use a 16-bit integer data type like `fixed-point` or `int16`.\n\n2. **Arduino Serial Send Block**:\n   - Add the `Serial Transmit` block from the Simulink Support Package for Arduino (`Simulink Support Package for Arduino > Common`).\n   - Double-click the `Serial Transmit` block to configure it:\n     - Set the `Port` to the serial port your Arduino is connected to (e.g., `COM3` on Windows).\n     - Set the `Baud rate` to match the baud rate configured in your Arduino code.\n\n3. **Data Type Conversion Block (if needed)**:\n   - If the data type of the `Constant` block is not compatible with the `Serial Transmit` block, you may need to add a `Data Type Conversion` block (`Simulink > Signal Attributes`).\n   - Set the output data type of the `Data Type Conversion` block to `uint16` or `int16`.\n\n### Step 4: Connect the Blocks\n1. Connect the `Constant` block to the `Serial Transmit` block.\n2. If you used a `Data Type Conversion` block, connect it between the `Constant` and `Serial Transmit` blocks.\n\n### Step 5: Configure the Simulation\n1. Open the **Model Configuration Parameters** by pressing `Ctrl+E` or by clicking on `Simulation > Model Configuration Parameters`.\n2. Under the `Solver` section, set the simulation time to a finite value (e.g., 10 seconds) or `inf` for continuous simulation.\n3. Under the `Hardware Implementation` section, select `Arduino` as the `Hardware board`.\n\n### Step 6: Deploy the Model to Arduino\n1. Click on the `Deploy to Hardware` button (the green play button with a down arrow) to compile and download the model to the Arduino.\n2. The Arduino will now send the 16-bit data over the serial port as specified in the Simulink model.\n\n### Example Arduino Code (Optional)\nIf you want to verify the data on the Arduino side, you can upload the following code to your Arduino:\n\n```cpp\nvoid setup() {\n  Serial.begin(9600); // Set the baud rate to match Simulink\n}\n\nvoid loop() {\n  if (Serial.available() >= 2) { // Ensure 16-bit data is available\n    uint16_t data = Serial.read(); // Read the first byte (LSB)\n    data |= Serial.read() << 8; // Read the second byte (MSB)\n    // Process or print the data as needed\n    Serial.print(\"Received 16-bit data: \");\n    Serial.println(data);\n  }\n}\n```\n\n### Summary\nBy following these steps, you can send 16-bit data from Simulink to an Arduino using the `Serial Transmit` block. Ensure that the data types and communication settings (e.g., baud rate) match between Simulink and the Arduino code.",
